PORTLAND, Maine — As concerns grow over the potential presence of federal immigration agents in Maine, business owners in Portland and Lewiston are taking precautions to protect their employees and customers.

Some small businesses have begun posting signs reading “No ICE” in their windows—an effort to make clear that Immigration and Customs Enforcement agents are not welcome without a warrant.

This comes after several [Maine state representatives warned the public](/article/news/local/maine-immigration/maine-leaders-warn-of-possible-increased-ice-presence-amid-unconfirmed-reports-portland-lewiston/97-d639c536-0d5a-49b6-b4fc-4cf38e628ca2) about a possible increase in immigration enforcement in southern Maine communities.

'“I'm scared for my colleagues, and I'm scared for my neighbors,” Andrew Volk, owner of The Portland Hunt and Alpine Club, said.

He’s been speaking with his staff about how to handle any unexpected visits from immigration agents. Volk said he made it clear that if that day comes, he’ll be the one to talk to authorities directly.

“Ensuring them that we may be respectful, but we aren’t welcoming to any federal agencies coming here,” he said. “It's something I would handle directly.”

**RELATED: [Maine leaders warn of possible increased ICE presence amid unconfirmed reports](/article/news/local/maine-immigration/maine-leaders-warn-of-possible-increased-ice-presence-amid-unconfirmed-reports-portland-lewiston/97-d639c536-0d5a-49b6-b4fc-4cf38e628ca2)**

Ilma Lopez, owner of Ugly Duckling Café and Chaval, is also preparing staff and putting up No ICE signs in her windows. As a Venezuelan immigrant who employs other immigrants, she said the uncertainty is unsettling.

“We’re trying to do everything by the rules, and to still not feel welcome—it’s hard,” Lopez said. “It’s really hard, and it's just because of where we're from."

She’s been holding meetings with her staff to go over what to do if ICE shows up and reminding them to carry identification at all times.

"We don't want to disrespect them, we don't want to be disrespected, we don't want to start a fight with them because we don't want them to fight with us," Lopez explained. "So it's more of a like, 'Hey, you're not welcome here this is a private space, let me know if you need something.'"

Business owners are within their rights to deny ICE entry unless agents present a judicial warrant, according to the ACLU of Maine.

