“If they have a judicial warrant, then let them in, and accommodate them as required,” chief counsel Zach Heiden said. “But you and your employees do not have to answer questions.”

It's not just small businesses preparing for the possibility of increased immigration enforcement. Hannaford, one of Maine’s largest grocery chains, also said it’s watching the situation closely.

“We are always monitoring these needs and deploy additional precautions as necessary,” a Hannaford spokesperson said in a statement. “We're committed to fostering a safe and welcoming environment for all customers and associates who shop or work at our stores.”

And while they plan on following the law, Lopez and Volk said their top priority is ensuring the safety and peace of mind of their staff and patrons—especially in a climate where immigrant communities feel vulnerable.

“Continue to make sure Maine is a welcoming place for everybody,” Volk said.

